One-sidedness in Texts

About this HHIT:
  1. Task
    • An argumentive text wants to convince you of something. Some texts are more one-sided than others.
    • We will present you two texts on a controversial topic side by side (A and B), each including four arguments.
    • An argument can be either "pro" or "con" regarding the controversial topic. This is called the stance. In the below examples, a "pro" stance, is indicated by green color, whereas a "con" stance is highlighted as red. For example:

    • We call a text one-sided if it includes more "pro" arguments than "con" arguments (or the other way around).
    • Objective: Given two texts A and B, determine which text is more one-sided than the other.
    • In Example 2, text A is more one-sided than B because it has more "pro" than "con" stances.
    • In Example 3, none of the texts is more one-sided because both have the same number of "con" stances.

  2. Disclaimer
    • You will not be compensated if:
    • You fail reading all the content, the system will detect if you don't read all the content.
    • You don't answer all the questions.
    • You participated more than one time. You can answer this survey only one time. The focus of the experiment is to get different participants. Therefore, we need unique participants for this study. The system will reject your work if it finds that you already participated. So please to avoid any impact on your approval rating, answer this survey only once.
